{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626378"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:37:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:37:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17073"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17073"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.47,0.14,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9763"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62906"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5265"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents with pulmonary tuberculosis. Laboratory testing confirms \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E that is sensitive to all first-line agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsoniazid is prescribed as part of the standard first-line treatment regimen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of isoniazid?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits RNA polymerase","Inhibits mycolic acid synthesis","Blocks protein synthesis at 30S ribosome","Inhibits DNA gyrase","Disrupts cell membrane integrity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits mycolic acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of isoniazid. It targets the enzyme enoyl-acyl carrier protein reductase (InhA), preventing the formation of mycolic acids which are essential components of the mycobacterial cell wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of rifampicin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks protein synthesis at 30S ribosome\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of aminoglycosides like streptomycin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits DNA gyrase\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of fluoroquinolones like moxifloxacin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a mechanism of first-line antimycobacterial drugs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsoniazid is bactericidal against actively growing \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E and is a crucial component of first-line tuberculosis treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Isoniazid inhibits mycolic acid synthesis in mycobacteria by targeting enoyl-acyl carrier protein reductase.","Rifampicin inhibits bacterial RNA synthesis by binding to DNA-dependent RNA polymerase.","First-line tuberculosis drugs primarily target cell wall synthesis or protein/nucleic acid synthesis."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62906"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17073"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62906"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:39:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T03:57:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9763"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77399"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u